Five predictors for compliance of SPs have been identified: knowledge of SPs, perceived barriers, perceived adequacy of training, perceived management support, and perceived influence of nursing staff (F6,605 = 15.085; P < .001) (Table 4
). The adjusted R
2 value was 0.122. This indicates that 12.2% of the variance in compliance of SPs was explained by the model. This small 12.2% variance indicated that the model explained only part, but not all, of the compliance of SPs among NSs. The perceived barriers included difficulty in performing procedures properly when wearing personal proactive equipment (39.3%, n = 247), offending patients when wearing personal proactive equipment to provide care (28.7%, n = 181), too busy to follow SPs (23.9%, n = 151), and offending nursing staff-ward practice if NSs followed proper SPs (22.7%, n = 143).
